  "final_answer": "The debate justified **buying camera c**.\n\n### Why this conclusion held\nThe strongest supported argument was:\n\n- **c is a camera**\n- **c has long battery life**\n- **c is user-friendly**\n- Therefore, **we should buy c**\n- Also, **b is over budget**, so **we should not buy b**\n\nThis argument stood because its key conditions for c were directly established in the AG1 stance, and the rule from “camera + long battery life + user-friendly” to “should buy” was never successfully overturned.\n\n### Key objections it had to survive\nAG2’s main counterargument tried to shift preference to **b** by claiming:\n\n- b is a camera\n- a is out of stock\n- b has long battery life\n- b has high image quality\n- therefore, **we should buy b**\n- and **we should not buy a**\n\nThis challenge did **not** defeat the justified conclusion for two reasons:\n\n1. **It did not undermine c’s purchase case.**  \n   Even if b had attractive features, that would only create a competing option. It did not show c should not be bought.\n\n2. **It failed against the explicit negative on b.**  \n   The debate also established **b is over budget**, and AG1’s rule says over-budget items should not be bought. That directly blocked b as the recommended purchase.\n\n### Why the competing objections were not enough\nAG2 also tried to support b via long battery life and high image quality, but those claims did not outweigh the clearer, more direct support for c plus the budget-based rejection of b. The discussion never produced a successful rebuttal to the fact that c met the buy conditions, while b was independently disqualified as over budget.\n\n### Final answer\n**We should buy c.**"
